{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Pescia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Pescia\n| latin             = Dioecesis Pisciensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Catedrale-pescia-facciata.jpg\n| image_size        =  \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = [[Pescia]] Cathedral\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[Italy]]\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Pisa|Pisa]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 224\n| population        = 122,200 (est.)\n| population_as_of  = 2016\n| catholics         = 112,600 (guess)<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = \n| parishes          = 41<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 15 April 1519 ({{age|1519|4|15}} years ago) \n| cathedral         = Cattedrale di Maria SS. Assunta e S. Giovanni Battista\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = \n| priests           = 47 (diocesan)<br />23 (Religious Orders)<br />6 Permanent Deacons<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Bishop\n| bishop            = [[Roberto Filippini]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Italy Tuscany Diocese map Pescia.svg\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.diocesidipescia.it/ www.diocesidipescia.it]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe Roman Catholic '''Diocese of Pescia''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Pisciensis}}) is in [[Tuscany]], about 41 miles (66&nbsp;km) west of Florence. It is a [[suffragan]] of the [[Archdiocese of Pisa]].<ref name=CathHierPescia>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dpesc.html \"Diocese of Pescia\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved 29 February 2016.{{Self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref name=GCathPescia>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/pesc1.htm \"Diocese of Pescia\"] ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved 29 February 2016.{{Self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=October 2016}}\n\n===Provostship===\nAs a favor to his Datary, Baldassare Turini, who was a cleric and notary of the diocese of Lucca, and Lorenzo de Cecchis, who was a ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'' and parish priest of the church of S. Maria Maggiore in Pescia, [[Pope Leo X]], in the bull \"Sacri Apostolatus\" of 15 April 1519, withdrew [[Pescia]] from the [[archdiocese of Lucca]], raising it to the dignity of a [[prelacy nullius]], and made it directly dependent upon the Holy See (Papacy). The territory was to become a Provostship, and De Cecchis was named the first Provost. A corporation of Canons. or Chapter, was established, with several dignities: the Provost, the Archdeacon, the Archpriest, the Dean, and the Primicerius. The territory of the new prelacy was to include all the churches in the Val di Nievole and the Valle Ariana. The Provost was assigned both ecclesiastical and civil jurisdiction (both of civil cases and criminal cases) in the Provostship.<ref>Cappelletti XVIII, pp. 323-340, quotes the bulls in their entirety.</ref>\n\nOn 23 September 1519, Leo X issued a second bull, \"Inter Caetera\", in which he authorized the Bishop of Pistoia, the Bishop of Forl\u00ec, and the Abbot of Vallombrosa, to perform the canonical investiture of the new Provost, Lorenzo de Cecchis. He also fixed the number of Canons of the collegiate church at twelve, and specified that the dignities were to be the Provost, the Archdeacon, the Rector of the church of S. Stefano in Pescia (who would have the title Prior), the Rector of Ss. Matteo e Colombano in Pietrobono (with the title of Archpriest), the Dean, the Treasurer, and the Primicerius.<ref>Cappelletti, p. 332.</ref>\n\nPope Leo X also granted to the provosts the right to use the vestments proper to a bishop, including mitre, staff, and cross, within the confines of their provostship. This was confirmed by [[Pope Urban VIII]] in the bull \"Dilecti filii\" of 25 February 1635, to which the pope added the right to wear the ''cappa magna'' and the ''mozzetta'', also within the confines of his jurisdiction.<ref>Cappelletti, pp. 355-356.</ref>\n\nA synod was held in the Provostship on 25\u201327 April 1694 by the Provost, Msgr. Benedetto Falconcini (1694-1704). The acts of the synod were published.<ref>{{cite book|author=Benedetto Falconcini|title=Decreta et constitutiones synodales eccl.ae praepositurae Piscien. habitae a reverendissimo domino d. Benedicto Falconcini ... die 25. 26. & 27. Aprilis 1694|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N-Ta00lUrGsC|year=1694|publisher=apud Petrum Matini praepositurae Piscien. typograph|location=Florence|language=Latin}}</ref>\n\n===Diocese===\nIn a bull of 17 March 1726, Pescia was established as a diocese by [[Pope Benedict XIII]], and made suffragan of (subordinate to) Pisa. The first bishop was, as was customary, the last Provost of the Collegiate Chapter, Paolo Antonio Pesenti, who had been in office since 1707. He was named Bishop-elect on 17 March 1727, but he died on 1 August 1728, before he was consecrated a bishop.<ref>Cappelletti XVIII, p. 358. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' V, p. 315, note 1.  A. Labardi, ''La comunit\u00e0 ecclesiastica pesciatina nel corso dei secoli. Percorsi storici di una Chiesa locale,'' in:  A. Spicciani (ed.), ''Pescia. La storia, l'arte e il costume,'' Pisa 2001, p. 87.</ref>\n\nSanta Maria Maggiore, dedicated to the taking up of the body of the Virgin Mary into heaven (Assumption), is referred to in documents as early as 991.<ref>Cappelletti, p. 561. Repetti, p. 131, credits its beginnings to the 8th century.</ref> The original church of the parish of Pescia, S. Maria Maggiore, which had been elevated to the status of a collegiate church, needed to be replaced. An enlarged church on the same site as the old church, and incorporating some of its elements, was constructed at the end of the 17th century, to designs by the Florentine architect, Antonio Ferri. The campanile is of the 14th century, though its uppermost part is of the late 18th century.<ref>Cappelletti, p. 358, quoting an inscription concerning the construction of the bell tower, dated 1306.</ref>\n\nIn 1742, the cathedral Chapter was composed of seven dignities and twelve Canons. The city of Pescia had about 5,000 inhabitants.<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VI, p. 339, note 1.</ref>\n\nIn 1784, with the cooperation of Grand Duke Leopold I, the diocesan seminary was opened.<ref>Repetti, p. 132 column 2.</ref>\n\nBy 1833, the population of the entire diocese of Pescia had risen to a total of 49,890 persons.<ref>Repetti, p. 134.</ref>\n\n==Bishops of Pescia==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Bartolomeo Pucci Franceschi (1728\u20131737)<ref>Pucci was a native of Montepulciano. Cappelletti, p. 370. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' V, p. 315, note 2.</ref>\n*Francesco Gaetano Incontri (1738\u20131741)<ref>A native of Volterra, Incontri was transferred to the [[Archbishop of Florence|diocese of Florence]] by [[Pope Clement XII]] on 5 May 1738. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VI, p. 339, with note 2.</ref>\n*Donato Maria Arcangeli (1742\u20131772)<ref>Arcangeli was a native of Arezzo. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VI, p. 340, with note 3.</ref>\n*Francesco Vincenti (1773\u20131803)<ref>Vincenti was a native of Livorno. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VI, p. 340, with note 4.</ref>\n*Giulio Rossi (1804\u20131833)<ref>Rossi: Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VII, p. 308.</ref>\n*Giovanni Battista Rossi (1834\u20131837)<ref>Rossi was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Pistoia e Prato|Pistoia e Prato]] by [[Pope Gregory XVI]] on 2 October 1837. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VII, p. 308.</ref>\n*Vincenzo Menchi (1839\u20131843)<ref>Menchi was appointed [[Bishop of Fiesole]] by [[Pope Gregory XVI]] on 30 January 1843. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VII, pp. 194, 308.</ref>\n*Pietro Niccol\u00f2 Forti (1847\u20131854)\n*Giovanni Antonio Benini (Bedini) (1855\u20131896)\n*Giulio Matteoli (1896\u20131898)<ref>Matteoli had been Bishop of Sovana e Pitigliano (1889\u20131896). He was transferred to Pescia on 22 June 1896 by [[Pope Leo XIII]]. On 24 March 1898, Matteoli was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Livorno]] by Leo XIII. He died on 25 July 1900. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VIII, pp. 342, 456, 523.</ref>\n*Donato Velluti Zati di San Clemente (1898\u20131907 Resigned)\n*Giulio Serafini (1907)<ref>Serafini was born in Bolsena (Orvieto). He studied at the Roman Pio Seminary in Rome, and held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]''. He taught at the seminary of Orvieto for five years, becoming its Rector. He was then Rector of the Roman Pio Seminary (1901\u20131913), and a papal chamberlain, while teaching at the seminary of S. Apollinaire. He was appointed Bishop of Pescia on 15 April 1907. He was named [[Titular Bishop]] of Lampsacus by [[Pope Pius X]] on 16 December 1907. On 30 June 1930, [[Pope Pius XI]] named him a cardinal. Pi\u0119ta, ''Hierarchia catholica'' IX, pp. 217, 302. {{cite book|author=Martin Br\u00e4uer|title=Handbuch der Kardin\u00e4le: 1846-2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=363pBQAAQBAJ&page=PA277|year=2014|publisher=De Gruyter|location=Berlin|language=German|isbn=978-3-11-026947-5|page=277}} {{cite book|author=Harris M. Lentz III|title=Popes and Cardinals of the 20th Century: A Biographical Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ongwCgAAQBAJ&pg=PR172|date=2002|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-2155-5|page=172}}</ref>\n*Angelo Simonetti (1907\u20131950)\n*Dino Luigi Romoli, [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (1951\u20131977 Retired)\n*Giovanni Bianchi (1977\u20131993 Retired)\n*Giovanni De Vivo (1993\u20132015 Died)\n*Roberto Filippini (2015\u2013 )\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Current Bishop===\n{{Overly detailed|section|date=November 2019}}\n\nOn 25 November 2015, [[Pope Francis]] appointed as the new Bishop of the Diocese of Pescia, in [[Pescia]], Italy, Roberto Filippini, S.T.L., a priest of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Pisa]]. Bishop Filippini was born in Vinci, [[Florence, Italy]], on 6 June 1948. He studied for his undergraduate [[philosophy]] degree in the Archdiocesan Seminary of Pisa. He completed his graduate theological studies at the [[Almo Collegio Capranica]], and attended the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] as well as the [[Pontifical Biblical Institute]], obtaining the [[Licentiate in Sacred Theology]] and in [[Sacred Scripture]]. He was ordained a priest on 14 April 1973, age 24, for the archdiocese of Pisa. He was Parochial Vicar (Associate [[Pastor]]) in the [[Parish]] of St. Hermes in Forte dei Marmi, Italy, from 1975 to 1978, and undertook teaching at the Seminary of Pisa. He was a Parish Priest in Calignola, Italy, from 1978 to 1984; from 1984 to 1997, Pastor of the Parish of [[Santo Sepolcro (Pisa)]] in Pisa; and from 1997, Parish Priest of San Martino, Italy. In 1996, he was appointed President of the Studio Teologico Interdiocesano di Camaiore (seminary) in [[Lucca, Italy]]. From 1999 to September 2015, Filippini was Rector of the Seminary \"Santa Caterina\" in Pisa. From 1999 to 2015, he served as a Prison Chaplain at a [[prison]] in Pisa. He has also been a [[Professor]] of [[Fundamental Theology]] and Sacred Scripture at the Higher Institute of Religious Sciences of Blessed [[Nicholas Steno]], in Pisa, and at the School of Theological Education.<ref>[http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2015/11/25/0919/02088.html Vatican Press Release, 25 November 2015.]</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon}} p.&nbsp;762. (Use with caution; obsolete)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi|volume=Tomus V (1667-1730)|date=1952|language=Latin|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi|volume=Tomus VI (1730-1799)|date=1958|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol06eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia Catholica medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgyItwAACAAJ|volume=Volume VII (1800\u20131846)|year=1968|publisher=Libreria Regensburgiana|location=Monasterii|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Remigius Ritzler|author2=Pirminus Sefrin|title=Hierarchia catholica Medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oXUjwEACAAJ|year=1978|volume=Volume VIII (1846\u20131903)|publisher=Il Messaggero di S. Antonio|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last= Pi\u0119ta|first=Zenon|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXuJQwAACAAJ|volume=Volume IX (1903\u20131922)|year=2002|publisher=Messagero di San Antonio|location=Padua|language=Latin|isbn=978-88-250-1000-8}}\n\n===Studies===\n*{{cite book|last=Ansaldi|first=Giuseppe|title=Cenni biografici dei personaggi illustri della citt\u00e0 di Pescia e suoi dintorni|url=https://archive.org/details/cennibiograficid00ansa|page=[https://archive.org/details/cennibiograficid00ansa/page/1 1]|year=1872|publisher=Tip. Vannini|location=Pescia|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last=Banti|first=Ottavio|title=Pescia: la citt\u00e0 e il Vescovato : nella bolla del papa Benedetto XIII del 17 marzo 1727|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ETfZAAAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=ETS|location=Pisa|language=italian|isbn=978-88-467-0662-1}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cappelletti|first=Giuseppe|title=Le chiese d'Italia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HD08AQAAIAAJ|volume=decimotto (18)|year=1864|publisher=G. Antonelli|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=321\u2013364}}\n*{{cite book|last=Nucci|first=Ermenegildo |title=I vescovi di Pescia dall'anno 1726 al 1908|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v_PBoQEACAAJ|year=1937|publisher=Stamperia G. Franchi|location=Pescia|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last=Repetti|first=Emanuele|title=Dizionario geografico fisico storico della Toscana contenente la descrizione di tutti i luoghi del Granducato, Ducato di Lucca Garfagnana e Lunigiana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7DvIoZeXZ1AC&pg=PA132|volume=Vol. IV (P-R)|year=1841|publisher=Allegrini e Mazzoni|location=Firenze|language=Italian|pages=113\u2013134}}\n*{{cite book|title=Storia della Val di Nievole dall'origine di Pescia fino all'anno 1818|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Xo5AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA386|year=1846|publisher=Cino|location=Pistoia|language=Italian}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Pisa}}\n\n{{coord|43.9000|N|10.6833|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Tuscany|Pescia]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in the 1510s]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses established in the 16th century|Pescia]]\n[[Category:1519 establishments in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Pescia\n| latin             = Dioecesis Pisciensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Catedrale-pescia-facciata.jpg\n| image_size        =  \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = [[Pescia]] Cathedral\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[Italy]]\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Pisa|Pisa]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 224\n| population        = 122,200 (est.)\n| population_as_of  = 2016\n| catholics         = 112,600 (guess)<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = \n| parishes          = 41<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 15 April 1519 ({{age|1519|4|15}} years ago) \n| cathedral         = Cattedrale di Maria SS. Assunta e S. Giovanni